<p>We could also orient the surface by 
choosing the normal vector $\pdiff{\dlsp}{\phi} \times
\pdiff{\dlsp}{\theta}$ instead of the vector $\pdiff{\dlsp}{\theta} \times \pdiff{\dlsp}{\phi}$ that we used above.  
How does the new normal vector orient the surface?</p>

<p>Recalling the properties
of the {%intlink cross_product %}cross product{%endintlink%},
we can conclude these vectors are opposites: $\displaystyle
\pdiff{\dlsp}{\phi} \times \pdiff{\dlsp}{\theta} = -\pdiff{\dlsp}{\theta} \times
\pdiff{\dlsp}{\phi}$.  In this case, unit normal is
\begin{align*}
  \vc{n} =  \frac{\displaystyle\pdiff{\dlsp}{\phi} \times  \pdiff{\dlsp}{\theta}}
  {\displaystyle\left\| \pdiff{\dlsp}{\phi} \times  \pdiff{\dlsp}{\theta} \right\|}
  = (\sin\phi \cos\theta, \sin\phi \sin\theta,\cos\phi)
\end{align*}
The normal vector points toward the outside the sphere, as shown below.  For this second
orientation of the sphere, the outside is the {%intlink positive_side_definition%}positive side{%endintlink%} of the
surface.
